Docker Volumes & Bind Mounts
Storage Types at a Glance
Type	Managed By	Location on Host	Use Case
volume	Docker	/var/lib/docker/volumes/	Production data persistence
bind mount	You	Any path you specify	Dev: live code reload
tmpfs	Kernel (RAM)	Memory only	Secrets, temp sensitive data

Step-by-Step Hands-On Practice
Step 1 — Understand the Problem (no persistence)
# Write data inside a container with NO volume
docker run --name no-persist alpine sh -c "echo 'important data' > /data/file.txt"
# Error: /data doesn't exist — let's use /tmp
docker run --name no-persist alpine sh -c "echo 'important data' > /tmp/file.txt"

# Container stops. Restart it.
docker start -ai no-persist

# Data is gone after rm
docker rm no-persist
docker run --rm alpine sh -c "cat /tmp/file.txt 2>/dev/null || echo 'DATA LOST'"

# Cleanup
docker rm -f no-persist 2>/dev/null; true

Step 2 — Named Volume (Docker-Managed)
# Create a named volume explicitly
docker volume create app-data

# Inspect it — see where Docker stores it on host
docker volume inspect app-data
# "Mountpoint": "/var/lib/docker/volumes/app-data/_data"

# List volumes
docker volume ls

Step 3 — Persist Data Across Container Restarts
# Run container 1 — WRITE data to the volume
docker run --rm \
  --name writer \
  -v app-data:/data \
  alpine sh -c "echo 'persisted across restarts' > /data/message.txt && cat /data/message.txt"

# Container is gone (--rm), but volume survives
# Run container 2 — READ the same volume
docker run --rm \
  --name reader \
  -v app-data:/data \
  alpine cat /data/message.txt

# Output: "persisted across restarts" ✓

Step 4 — Persist a Database (Real-World Pattern)
# Create volume for postgres data
docker volume create pgdata

# Start postgres with volume
docker run -d \
  --name mydb \
  -e POSTGRES_PASSWORD=secret \
  -e POSTGRES_DB=myapp \
  -v pgdata:/var/lib/postgresql/data \
  postgres:16-alpine

# Wait for DB to be ready, then insert data
sleep 3
docker exec -it mydb psql -U postgres -d myapp \
  -c "CREATE TABLE users (id SERIAL, name TEXT); INSERT INTO users(name) VALUES ('Alice'),('Bob');"

# STOP and REMOVE the container completely
docker rm -f mydb

# Start a BRAND NEW container using the same volume
docker run -d \
  --name mydb-new \
  -e POSTGRES_PASSWORD=secret \
  -e POSTGRES_DB=myapp \
  -v pgdata:/var/lib/postgresql/data \
  postgres:16-alpine

sleep 3

# Query — data is still there!
docker exec mydb-new psql -U postgres -d myapp -c "SELECT * FROM users;"
#  id | name
# ----+-------
#   1 | Alice
#   2 | Bob    ✓

docker rm -f mydb-new

Step 5 — Bind Mount (Live Code Reload for Dev)
mkdir -p ~/demo-app
echo "<h1>Version 1</h1>" > ~/demo-app/index.html

# Mount local directory into nginx
docker run -d \
  --name devserver \
  -p 8080:80 \
  -v ~/demo-app:/usr/share/nginx/html:ro \
  nginx:alpine

curl http://localhost:8080
# <h1>Version 1</h1>

# Edit on HOST — change reflects immediately, no rebuild!
echo "<h1>Version 2 — Live Reload!</h1>" > ~/demo-app/index.html

curl http://localhost:8080
# <h1>Version 2 — Live Reload!</h1>  ✓

docker rm -f devserver
:ro = read-only inside container. Container cannot write back to your host files.


Step 6 — Bind Mount vs Volume Side-by-Side
# Bind mount — you control the path
docker run --rm \
  -v /tmp/mydata:/data \
  alpine sh -c "echo 'bind mount' > /data/test.txt && cat /data/test.txt"

cat /tmp/mydata/test.txt   # readable directly on host ✓

# Named volume — Docker controls the path
docker run --rm \
  -v myvolume:/data \
  alpine sh -c "echo 'named volume' > /data/test.txt && cat /data/test.txt"

# To read it on host (need sudo or docker cp):
docker run --rm -v myvolume:/data alpine cat /data/test.txt  ✓

# Cleanup
docker volume rm myvolume

Step 7 — tmpfs Mount (Sensitive Data in RAM)
# Data written to tmpfs NEVER touches disk
docker run -it --rm \
  --tmpfs /secrets:rw,size=64m,mode=1700 \
  alpine sh -c "
    echo 'api-key-12345' > /secrets/key.txt
    cat /secrets/key.txt
    echo 'This never hits the disk'
  "
# When container stops, /secrets is wiped from RAM

Step 8 — Volume Operations (Backup, Restore, Copy)
# BACKUP a volume to a tar file on host
docker run --rm \
  -v app-data:/source:ro \
  -v $(pwd):/backup \
  alpine tar czf /backup/app-data-backup.tar.gz -C /source .

ls -lh app-data-backup.tar.gz  # backup file on host ✓

# RESTORE into a new volume
docker volume create app-data-restored
docker run --rm \
  -v app-data-restored:/target \
  -v $(pwd):/backup \
  alpine tar xzf /backup/app-data-backup.tar.gz -C /target

# Verify restore
docker run --rm -v app-data-restored:/data alpine cat /data/message.txt

# Copy a single file out of a volume (no running container needed)
docker create --name temp-container -v app-data:/data alpine
docker cp temp-container:/data/message.txt ./recovered-message.txt
docker rm temp-container

# Cleanup
docker volume rm app-data app-data-restored

Step 9 — Volume in Docker Compose
docker-compose.yml:
version: "3.9"

services:
  db:
    image: postgres:16-alpine
    environment:
      POSTGRES_PASSWORD: secret
    volumes:
      - pgdata:/var/lib/postgresql/data   # named volume

  api:
    image: node:20-alpine
    working_dir: /app
    volumes:
      - ./src:/app/src                    # bind mount for live dev
      - node_modules:/app/node_modules    # volume so host doesn't overwrite
    command: sh -c "npm install && node src/index.js"

  cache:
    image: redis:7-alpine
    volumes:
      - type: tmpfs                       # tmpfs for ephemeral cache
        target: /data

volumes:
  pgdata:         # Docker-managed, persists between `compose down`
  node_modules:   # Prevents host node_modules from shadowing container's

docker compose up -d
docker compose down        # volumes SURVIVE
docker compose down -v     # volumes DELETED (careful!)

Step 10 — Prune and Manage Volumes
# List all volumes
docker volume ls

# Show dangling volumes (not attached to any container)
docker volume ls -f dangling=true

# Remove a specific volume
docker volume rm pgdata

# Remove ALL unused volumes (dangerous — confirm first)
docker volume prune -f

Interview Questions & Answers
Conceptual
Q1: What is the difference between a volume and a bind mount?

Volume: managed by Docker, stored in /var/lib/docker/volumes/, portable, works on any OS, preferred for production. Bind mount: maps a specific host path into the container, you manage it, ideal for dev (live reload). Volumes are safer — Docker controls them and they're not accidentally deleted by host operations.

Q2: Why use a named volume instead of an anonymous volume?

Named volumes are explicitly referenced by name, easy to reuse across containers, and won't be garbage-collected by docker volume prune as easily as anonymous ones. Anonymous volumes (created by VOLUME in Dockerfile with no name) are harder to track.

Q3: What is tmpfs and when would you use it?

A tmpfs mount stores data in host RAM — never written to disk. Use it for sensitive data (tokens, session keys), cache that should not persist, or performance-critical temp storage.

Q4: What does the VOLUME instruction in a Dockerfile do?

It declares a mount point and creates an anonymous volume at runtime if no -v is specified. It does NOT define what gets mounted — that's the runtime's job. It's a hint that data at that path should be persisted.

Q5: Does docker compose down delete volumes?

No, by default down preserves volumes. Use docker compose down -v or --volumes to also delete the named volumes defined in the Compose file.

Practical / Scenario-Based
Q6: A developer says "my DB data is lost every time the container restarts." What's wrong?

No volume is mounted. The data lives only in the container's writable layer. Fix: add -v pgdata:/var/lib/postgresql/data. Also verify they're not running docker rm (which removes the container layer) vs just stopping it.

Q7: You need to share a volume between two containers simultaneously. How?

Mount the same named volume in both containers:

docker run -d -v shared-data:/data --name c1 alpine sleep 3600
docker run -d -v shared-data:/data --name c2 alpine sleep 3600

Both can read/write. Implement file locking in your app to avoid race conditions.

Q8: How do you migrate a volume's data to a new server?

docker run --rm -v oldvolume:/src -v $(pwd):/backup alpine tar czf /backup/vol.tar.gz -C /src .
Transfer vol.tar.gz to new server (scp/rsync)
docker volume create newvolume
docker run --rm -v newvolume:/target -v $(pwd):/backup alpine tar xzf /backup/vol.tar.gz -C /target

Q9: What's the node_modules volume trick in Compose and why is it needed?

When bind-mounting ./src:/app on a host that has no node_modules (or a different OS), the host directory overwrites the container's node_modules. The fix is a separate named volume for node_modules which takes precedence over the bind mount for that specific subdirectory.

Q10: How do you make a bind mount read-only?

Append :ro — -v /host/path:/container/path:ro. The container can read but cannot write back to the host path. Useful for config files and static assets.

Security-Focused
Q11: What are the security risks of bind mounts?

Mounting / or /etc exposes the entire host filesystem
A compromised container can modify host files if the mount is writable
Mounting the Docker socket (/var/run/docker.sock) gives the container full Docker control = root on host
Always use :ro where writes aren't needed and never mount the Docker socket in production
Q12: Are volumes encrypted at rest?

Not by default. Docker volumes are plain directories on the host. For encryption, use encrypted host filesystems (LUKS), encrypted storage drivers, or cloud provider volume encryption (EBS, Azure Disk).

